SIMPLE: toil
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Toil
<hw>Toil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>toiles</ets>,
pl., toils, nets, fr. <ets>toile</ets> cloth, canvas, spider web, fr. L.
<ets>tela</ets> any woven stuff, a web, fr. <ets>texere</ets> to weave.
See <er>Text</er>, and cf. <er>Toilet</er>.]</ety> <def>A net or snare;
any thread, web, or string spread for taking prey; -- usually in the
plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As a Numidian lion, when first caught,⟦br⟧
Endures the <qex>toil</qex> that holds him.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then <qex>toils</qex> for beasts, and lime for birds, were
found.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Toil
<hw>Toil</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Toiled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Toiling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>toilen</ets> to pull
about, to toil; of uncertain origin; cf. OD. <ets>teulen</ets>,
<ets>tuylen</ets>, to labor, till, or OF. <ets>tooillier</ets>,
<ets>toailler</ets>, to wash, rub (cf. <er>Towel</er>); or perhaps
ultimately from the same root as E. <ets>tug</ets>.]</ety> <def>To exert
strength with pain and fatigue of body or mind, especially of the body,
with efforts of some continuance or duration; to labor; to
work.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Toil
<hw>Toil</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To weary; to
overlabor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Toiled</xex> with works
of war.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To labor; to work; -- often with
<xex>out</xex>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Places well <qex>toiled</qex> and husbanded.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I] <qex>toiled</qex> out my uncouth passage.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1515 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Toil
<hw>Toil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>toil</ets>
turmoil, struggle; cf. OD. <ets>tuyl</ets> labor, work. See
<er>Toil</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>Labor with pain and fatigue;
labor that oppresses the body or mind, esp. the body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My task of servile <qex>toil</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After such bloody <qex>toil</qex>, we bid good night.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Toil</xex> is used in the formation of compounds
which are generally of obvious signification; as,
<xex>toil</xex>-strung, <xex>toil</xex>-wasted, <xex>toil</xex>-worn,
and the like.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Labor; drudgery; work; exertion; occupation;
employment; task; travail.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Toil</er>,
<er>Labor</er>, <er>Drudgery</er>. <xex>Labor</xex> implies strenuous
exertion, but not necessary such as overtasks the faculties;
<xex>toil</xex> denotes a severity of labor which is painful and
exhausting; <xex>drudgery</xex> implies mean and degrading work, or, at
least, work which wearies or disgusts from its minuteness or dull
uniformity.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You do not know the heavy grievances,⟦br⟧
The <qex>toils</qex>, the <qex>labors</qex>, weary
<qex>drudgeries</qex>,⟦br⟧
Which they impose.</q> <rj><qau>Southern.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How often have I blessed the coming day,⟦br⟧
When <qex>toil</qex> remitting lent its turn to play.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toiler</ent>⟦br⟧
